27. Existence of $h^{\#}$

In solving (26.90), it is useful to introduce an auxiliary norm for the space $Y_{N}$ defined in (26.7), as follows.

For $x$ fixed, define $A_{x}:H^{1}(\Sigma )\rightarrow L^{2}(\Sigma )$

27.1 $$\begin{equation} (A_{x}g)(z)\equiv \frac{dg}{dz}(z)+ixg(z)J_{-}(z),\qquad g\in H^{1}(\Sigma ), \cssId{texmlid567}{\tag{27.1}} \end{equation}$$

for $z\in \Sigma \backslash 0$, and for $g\in H^{N}(\Sigma )$, set

27.2 $$\begin{equation} \Vert g\Vert _{N,x}=\sum _{j=0}^{N}\Vert A_{x}^{j}g\Vert _{L^{2}(\Sigma )}. \cssId{texmlid568}{\tag{27.2}} \end{equation}$$

Finally, for $N,\, x$ fixed, define

27.3 $$\begin{equation} |h|_{x}=\Vert h|_{\Sigma \backslash 0}\Vert _{N,x}+\sum _{j}\Vert h(z_{j})\Vert \cssId{texmlid569}{\tag{27.3}} \end{equation}$$

for $h\in Y_{N}$. For $x$ fixed, $|\cdot |_{x}$ is clearly equivalent to $|\cdot |$ in (26.8).
